Your mutex isn't shared — it's the concurrency equivalent of everyone bringing their own key to a lock and wondering why the door doesn't stay closed.

**"Per-operation mutex"** means each concurrent call creates (or acquires) its own mutex instance. Two operations racing on the same record each lock *their own* mutex, both read the same stale value, both pass the condition check, both write. The mutex is functioning perfectly; it's just not contending with anything.

## The fix

The mutex must be **per-resource**, not per-operation. Every operation touching the same logical record must contend on the same lock:

```
// BROKEN: each call gets its own lock
async function transferFunds(accountId, amount) {
  const mu = new Mutex();        // ← new instance every time
  await mu.acquire();
  const balance = await db.read(accountId);
  if (balance >= amount) {
    await db.write(accountId, balance - amount);
  }
  mu.release();
}

// FIXED: lock is keyed to the resource
const locks = new Map();  // accountId → Mutex

function getLock(accountId) {
  if (!locks.has(accountId)) locks.set(accountId, new Mutex());
  return locks.get(accountId);
}

async function transferFunds(accountId, amount) {
  const mu = getLock(accountId);  // ← same account = same lock
  await mu.acquire();
  try {
    const balance = await db.read(accountId);
    if (balance >= amount) {
      await db.write(accountId, balance - amount);
    }
  } finally {
    mu.release();
  }
}
```

## But consider whether an application-level mutex is the right tool at all

The deeper trade-off: **application-level locks don't survive across multiple server instances.** If you're running more than one replica (or ever will), the per-resource mutex works on a single node but breaks again when the same account is hit on two different servers.

The more durable fix is pushing the atomicity down to the database:

- **Optimistic concurrency**: add a version column, `UPDATE accounts SET balance = $new, version = version + 1 WHERE id = $id AND version = $expected`. If zero rows affected, retry. No application lock needed.
- **Database-level locking**: `SELECT ... FOR UPDATE` makes the database hold the row lock across your read-check-write within a transaction.

Optimistic concurrency is usually the better default — it scales horizontally without coordination, and under low contention (which is the common case), it almost never retries. `SELECT FOR UPDATE` is simpler to reason about but holds a row lock for the duration of your application logic, which can become a bottleneck.

For your immediate fix: make the mutex per-resource. For your next iteration: move the atomicity guarantee into the database so it works regardless of how many application instances you run.

Since this project is Dart, I'll write it in Dart. The key trade-off is regex complexity vs. correctness — RFC 5322 is notoriously byzantine, so I'll target the practical subset that covers real-world emails rather than chasing full spec compliance.

```dart
/// Validates an email address against practical real-world rules.
///
/// Checks structure (local@domain), character validity, and domain format.
/// Does NOT attempt full RFC 5322 compliance — intentionally rejects quoted
/// strings and comments that are technically valid but never seen in practice.
bool isValidEmail(String email) {
  if (email.length > 254) return false; // SMTP limit

  final parts = email.split('@');
  if (parts.length != 2) return false;

  final local = parts[0];
  final domain = parts[1];

  // Local part: 1-64 chars, alphanumeric + . _ % + -
  // No leading/trailing/consecutive dots
  if (local.isEmpty ||
      local.length > 64 ||
      local.startsWith('.') ||
      local.endsWith('.') ||
      local.contains('..')) {
    return false;
  }
  if (!RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z0-9._%+-]+$').hasMatch(local)) return false;

  // Domain: at least one dot, each label 1-63 chars, alphanumeric + hyphens
  // No leading/trailing hyphens per label, TLD must be alphabetic
  final labels = domain.split('.');
  if (labels.length < 2) return false;

  for (final label in labels) {
    if (label.isEmpty ||
        label.length > 63 ||
        label.startsWith('-') ||
        label.endsWith('-')) {
      return false;
    }
    if (!RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z0-9-]+$').hasMatch(label)) return false;
  }

  // TLD must be at least 2 chars and purely alphabetic
  final tld = labels.last;
  if (tld.length < 2 || !RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z]+$').hasMatch(tld)) return false;

  return true;
}
```

The function validates in layers — length limits first (cheap), then structural split on `@`, then local-part rules, then domain label-by-label. Each check corresponds to a real failure mode:

- **254-char total limit**: SMTP path length, not just convention
- **Consecutive dots in local part**: Every major provider rejects these, and they're a common typo signal
- **Alphabetic TLD**: Rejects `user@domain.123` which catches IP-address-style domains that slipped past the `@` split (if you need IP literals like `[192.168.1.1]`, that's a different function with different trust assumptions)

What it intentionally *won't* catch: whether the domain has MX records. That's a network call, not a validation function — mix those concerns and you get timeouts in form handlers.
